<div class=3D"paragraph" style=3D"text-align:justify;"><font size=3D"4"><u>=
<strong>Decryption</strong></u></font><br><span></span>To decrypt a ciphert=
ext encoded using the Hill Cipher, we must find the inverse matrix. Once we=
 have the inverse matrix, the process is the same as encrypting. That is we=
 multiply the inverse key matrix by the column vectors that the ciphertext =
is split into, take the results modulo the length of the alphabet, and fina=
lly convert the numbers back to letters.<br><span></span></div>

<div class=3D"paragraph" style=3D"text-align:justify;">Since the majority o=
f the process is the same as encryption, we are going ot focus on finding t=
he inverse key matrix (not an easy task), and will then skim quickly throug=
h the other steps (for more information see Encryption above).<br></div>

<div class=3D"paragraph" style=3D"text-align:justify;">In general, to find =
the inverse of the key matrix, we perform the calculation below, where <em>=
K</em> is the key matrix, <em>d</em> is the determinant of the key matrix a=
nd <em>adj</em>(<em>K</em>) is the adjugate matrix of K.<br></div>

<div><div class=3D"wsite-image wsite-image-border-none " style=3D"padding-t=
op:10px;padding-bottom:10px;margin-left:0;margin-right:0;text-align:center"=
