<div class=3D"paragraph" style=3D"text-align:justify;"><u>Step 1 - Find the=
 Multiplicative Inverse of the Determinant</u><br><span></span>The <a title=
=3D"" target=3D"_blank" href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Determinant">d=
eterminant</a> is a number that relates directly to the entries of the matr=
ix. It is found by multiplying the top left number by the bottom right numb=
er and subtracting from this the product of the top right number and the bo=
ttom left number. This is shown algebraically below. Note that the notation=
 for determinant has straight lines instead of brackets around our matrix.<=
br></div>

<div><div class=3D"wsite-image wsite-image-border-none " style=3D"padding-t=
op:10px;padding-bottom:10px;margin-left:0;margin-right:0;text-align:center"=
>
<a href=3D"https://crypto.interactive-maths.com/uploads/1/1/3/4/11345755/45=
33438_orig.jpg" class=3D"w-fancybox">
<img src=3D"https://crypto.interactive-maths.com/uploads/1/1/3/4/11345755/4=
533438_orig.jpg" alt=3D"Picture" style=3D"width:100%;max-width:290px">
</a>
<div style=3D"display:block;font-size:90%">Algebraic method to calculate th=
e determinant of a 2 x 2 matrix.</div>
</div></div>

<div class=3D"paragraph" style=3D"text-align:justify;">Once we have found t=
his value, we need to take the number modulo 26. Below is the way to calcul=
ate the determinant for our example.<br></div>

<div><div class=3D"wsite-image wsite-image-border-none " style=3D"padding-t=
op:10px;padding-bottom:10px;margin-left:0;margin-right:0;text-align:center"=
>
<a href=3D"https://crypto.interactive-maths.com/uploads/1/1/3/4/11345755/64=
