<img src=3D"https://crypto.interactive-maths.com/uploads/1/1/3/4/11345755/6=
449828_orig.jpg" alt=3D"Picture" style=3D"width:100%;max-width:759px">
</a>
<div style=3D"display:block;font-size:90%">Calculating the determinant of o=
ur 2 x 2 key matrix.</div>
</div></div>

<div><div class=3D"wsite-multicol"><div class=3D"wsite-multicol-table-wrap"=
 style=3D"margin:0 -15px;">
	<table class=3D"wsite-multicol-table">
		<tbody class=3D"wsite-multicol-tbody">
			<tr class=3D"wsite-multicol-tr">
				<td class=3D"wsite-multicol-col" style=3D"width:62.253521126761%; paddi=
ng:0 15px;">
				=09
					=09

<div class=3D"paragraph" style=3D"text-align:justify;">We now have to find =
the <a title=3D"" target=3D"_blank" href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mo=
dular_multiplicative_inverse">multiplicative inverse of the determinant wor=
king modulo</a> 26. That is, the number between 1 and 25 that gives an answ=
er of 1 when we multiply it by the determinant. So, in this case, we are lo=
oking for the number that we need to multiply 15 by to get an answer of 1 m=
odulo 26. There are algorithms to calculate this, but it is often easiest t=
o use trial and error to find the inverse.<br></div>


				=09
				</td>				<td class=3D"wsite-multicol-col" style=3D"width:37.74647887323=
9%; padding:0 15px;">
				=09
					=09

<div><div class=3D"wsite-image wsite-image-border-none " style=3D"padding-t=
op:10px;padding-bottom:10px;margin-left:0;margin-right:0;text-align:center"=
>
<a href=3D"https://crypto.interactive-maths.com/uploads/1/1/3/4/11345755/85=
9481_orig.jpg" class=3D"w-fancybox">
<img src=3D"https://crypto.interactive-maths.com/uploads/1/1/3/4/11345755/8=
59481_orig.jpg" alt=3D"Picture" style=3D"width:100%;max-width:289px">
</a>
<div style=3D"display:block;font-size:90%">If d is the determinant, then we=
 are looking for the inverse of d.</div>
</div></div>

<div><div class=3D"wsite-image wsite-image-border-none " style=3D"padding-t=
op:10px;padding-bottom:10px;margin-left:0;margin-right:0;text-align:center"=
>
<a href=3D"https://crypto.interactive-maths.com/uploads/1/1/3/4/11345755/51=
90131_orig.jpg" class=3D"w-fancybox">
<img src=3D"https://crypto.interactive-maths.com/uploads/1/1/3/4/11345755/5=
190131_orig.jpg" alt=3D"Picture" style=3D"width:100%;max-width:304px">
</a>
<div style=3D"display:block;font-size:90%">The multiplicative inverse is th=
e number we multiply 15 by to get 1 modulo 26.</div>
</div></div>


				=09
				</td>			</tr>
		</tbody>
	</table>
</div></div></div>

<div><div class=3D"wsite-image wsite-image-border-none " style=3D"padding-t=
op:10px;padding-bottom:10px;margin-left:0;margin-right:0;text-align:center"=
>
<a href=3D"https://crypto.interactive-maths.com/uploads/1/1/3/4/11345755/27=
04112_orig.jpg" class=3D"w-fancybox">
<img src=3D"https://crypto.interactive-maths.com/uploads/1/1/3/4/11345755/2=
704112_orig.jpg" alt=3D"Picture" style=3D"width:100%;max-width:404px">
</a>
<div style=3D"display:block;font-size:90%">This calculation gives us an ans=
wer of 1 modulo 26.</div>
</div></div>

<div class=3D"paragraph" style=3D"text-align:justify;">So the multiplicativ=
e inverse of the determinant modulo 26 is 7. We shall need this number late=
r.<br></div>

<div class=3D"paragraph" style=3D"text-align:justify;"><u>Step 2 - Find the=
 Adjugate Matrix</u><br><span>The <a title=3D"" target=3D"_blank" href=3D"h=
ttp://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adjugate_matrix">adjugate matrix</a> is a matri=
x of the same size as the original.</span> For a 2 x 2 matrix, this is fair=
ly straightforward as it is just moving the elements to different positions=
 and changing a couple of signs. That is, we swap the top left and bottom r=
ight numbers in the key matrix, and change the sign of the the top right an=
d bottom left numbers. Algebraically this is given below.<br></div>

<div><div class=3D"wsite-image wsite-image-border-none " style=3D"padding-t=
op:10px;padding-bottom:10px;margin-left:0;margin-right:0;text-align:center"=
>
<a href=3D"https://crypto.interactive-maths.com/uploads/1/1/3/4/11345755/24=
75976_orig.jpg" class=3D"w-fancybox">
<img src=3D"https://crypto.interactive-maths.com/uploads/1/1/3/4/11345755/2=
475976_orig.jpg" alt=3D"Picture" style=3D"width:100%;max-width:390px">
</a>
<div style=3D"display:block;font-size:90%">The adjugate matrix of a 2 x 2 m=
atrix.</div>
</div></div>

<div class=3D"paragraph" style=3D"text-align:justify;">Again, once we have =
these values we will need to take each of them modulo 26 (in particular, we=
 need to add 26 to the negative values to get a number between 0 and 25. Fo=
r our example we get the matrix below.<br></div>

<div><div class=3D"wsite-image wsite-image-border-none " style=3D"padding-t=
op:10px;padding-bottom:10px;margin-left:0;margin-right:0;text-align:center"=
>
