<div class=3D"paragraph" style=3D"text-align:justify;"><u>Step 1 - Find the=
 Multiplicative Inverse of the Determinant</u><br><span></span>The <a title=
=3D"" target=3D"_blank" href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Determinant">d=
eterminant</a> is a number that relates directly to the entries of the matr=
ix. For a 3 x 3 matrix it is found by multiplying the top left entry by the=
 determinant of the 2 x 2 matrix formed by the entries that are not in the =
same row or column as that entry (that is the 2 x 2 matrix not including th=
e top row or left column). Similar steps are done with the other two elemen=
ts in the top row, and the middle value is subtracted from the sum of the o=
ther two. This is shown more clearly in the algebraic version below.<br></d=
iv>

<div><div class=3D"wsite-image wsite-image-border-none " style=3D"padding-t=
op:10px;padding-bottom:10px;margin-left:0;margin-right:0;text-align:center"=
>
<a href=3D"https://crypto.interactive-maths.com/uploads/1/1/3/4/11345755/44=
58084_orig.jpg" class=3D"w-fancybox">
<img src=3D"https://crypto.interactive-maths.com/uploads/1/1/3/4/11345755/4=
458084_orig.jpg" alt=3D"Picture" style=3D"width:100%;max-width:822px">
</a>
<div style=3D"display:block;font-size:90%">The algebraic representation of =
finding the determinant of a 3 x 3 matrix.</div>
</div></div>

<div class=3D"paragraph" style=3D"text-align:justify;">Once we have calcula=
ted this value, we take it modulo 26.<br></div>

<div><div class=3D"wsite-image wsite-image-border-none " style=3D"padding-t=
op:10px;padding-bottom:10px;margin-left:0;margin-right:0;text-align:center"=
>
<a href=3D"https://crypto.interactive-maths.com/uploads/1/1/3/4/11345755/80=
73467_orig.jpg" class=3D"w-fancybox">
<img src=3D"https://crypto.interactive-maths.com/uploads/1/1/3/4/11345755/8=
073467_orig.jpg" alt=3D"Picture" style=3D"width:100%;max-width:816px">
</a>
<div style=3D"display:block;font-size:90%">Finding the determinant of the 3=
 x 3 matrix with keyword alphabet.</div>
</div></div>

<div><div class=3D"wsite-multicol"><div class=3D"wsite-multicol-table-wrap"=
 style=3D"margin:0 -15px;">
	<table class=3D"wsite-multicol-table">
		<tbody class=3D"wsite-multicol-tbody">
			<tr class=3D"wsite-multicol-tr">
				<td class=3D"wsite-multicol-col" style=3D"width:62.253521126761%; paddi=
ng:0 15px;">
				=09
					=09

<div class=3D"paragraph" style=3D"text-align:justify;">We now have to find =
the <a title=3D"" target=3D"_blank" href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mo=
dular_multiplicative_inverse">multiplicative inverse of the determinant wor=
king modulo</a> 26. That is, the number between 1 and 25 that gives an answ=
er of 1 when we multiply it by the determinant. So, in this case, we are lo=
oking for the number that we need to multiply 11 by to get an answer of 1 m=
odulo 26. There are algorithms to calculate this, but it is often easiest t=
o use trial and error to find the inverse.<br></div>


				=09
				</td>				<td class=3D"wsite-multicol-col" style=3D"width:37.74647887323=
9%; padding:0 15px;">
				=09
					=09

<div><div class=3D"wsite-image wsite-image-border-none " style=3D"padding-t=
op:10px;padding-bottom:10px;margin-left:0;margin-right:0;text-align:center"=
>
<a href=3D"https://crypto.interactive-maths.com/uploads/1/1/3/4/11345755/80=
78788_orig.jpg" class=3D"w-fancybox">
<img src=3D"https://crypto.interactive-maths.com/uploads/1/1/3/4/11345755/8=
078788.jpg" alt=3D"Picture" style=3D"width:100%;max-width:304px">
</a>
<div style=3D"display:block;font-size:90%">The multiplicative inverse is th=
e number we multiply 11 by to get 1 modulo 26.</div>
</div></div>

<div><div class=3D"wsite-image wsite-image-border-none " style=3D"padding-t=
op:10px;padding-bottom:10px;margin-left:0;margin-right:0;text-align:center"=
>
<a href=3D"https://crypto.interactive-maths.com/uploads/1/1/3/4/11345755/_8=
59481_orig.jpg" class=3D"w-fancybox">
<img src=3D"https://crypto.interactive-maths.com/uploads/1/1/3/4/11345755/_=
859481_orig.jpg" alt=3D"Picture" style=3D"width:100%;max-width:289px">
</a>
<div style=3D"display:block;font-size:90%">If d is the determinant, then we=
 are looking for the inverse of d.</div>
</div></div>


				=09
				</td>			</tr>
		</tbody>
	</table>
</div></div></div>

<div><div class=3D"wsite-image wsite-image-border-none " style=3D"padding-t=
op:10px;padding-bottom:10px;margin-left:0;margin-right:0;text-align:center"=
>
<a href=3D"https://crypto.interactive-maths.com/uploads/1/1/3/4/11345755/15=
71506_orig.jpg" class=3D"w-fancybox">
<img src=3D"https://crypto.interactive-maths.com/uploads/1/1/3/4/11345755/1=
571506_orig.jpg" alt=3D"Picture" style=3D"width:100%;max-width:422px">
</a>
<div style=3D"display:block;font-size:90%">Finding the multiplicative inver=
se of 11 modulo 26.</div>
</div></div>

<div class=3D"paragraph" style=3D"text-align:justify;">So the multiplicativ=
e inverse of the determinant modulo 26 is 19. We shall need this number lat=
er.<br></div>

<div class=3D"paragraph" style=3D"text-align:justify;"><u>Step 2 - Find the=
 Adjugate Matrix</u><br><span>The <a title=3D"" target=3D"_blank" href=3D"h=
ttp://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adjugate_matrix">adjugate matrix</a> is a matri=
x of the same size as the original.</span> For a 3 x 3 matrix this process =
is somewhat more complex than it was for a 2 x 2 matrix. It requires us to =
calculate 9 lots of 2 x 2 determinants, and assign them with the correct si=
gns, and put them in the correct places. The algebraic representation is gi=
ven below.<br></div>

<div><div class=3D"wsite-image wsite-image-border-none " style=3D"padding-t=
op:10px;padding-bottom:10px;margin-left:0;margin-right:0;text-align:center"=
>
<a href=3D"https://crypto.interactive-maths.com/uploads/1/1/3/4/11345755/96=
13397_orig.jpg" class=3D"w-fancybox">
<img src=3D"https://crypto.interactive-maths.com/uploads/1/1/3/4/11345755/9=
613397_orig.jpg" alt=3D"Picture" style=3D"width:100%;max-width:812px">
</a>
<div style=3D"display:block;font-size:90%">Calculating the adjugate matrix =
of a 3 x 3 matrix.</div>
</div></div>

<div class=3D"paragraph" style=3D"text-align:justify;">Although this seems =
a bit of a random selection of letters to place in each of the discriminant=
s, it is defined as the transpose of the cofactor matrix, which is much eas=
ier to remember how to work out. To find the cofactor matrix, we take the 2=
 x 2 determinant in each position such that the four values in that positio=
n are the four values not in the same row or column as the position in the =
original matrix. The adjugate is then formed by reflecting the cofactor mat=
rix along the line from top left ot bottom right.<br></div>

<div><div class=3D"wsite-image wsite-image-border-none " style=3D"padding-t=
op:10px;padding-bottom:10px;margin-left:0;margin-right:0;text-align:center"=
>
<a href=3D"https://crypto.interactive-maths.com/uploads/1/1/3/4/11345755/74=
57658_orig.jpg" class=3D"w-fancybox">
<img src=3D"https://crypto.interactive-maths.com/uploads/1/1/3/4/11345755/7=
457658_orig.jpg" alt=3D"Picture" style=3D"width:100%;max-width:900px">
</a>
<div style=3D"display:block;font-size:90%">The cofactor matrix can be used =
to find the adjugate matrix. Simply reflect it along the line from top left=
 ot bottom right of the matrix.</div>
</div></div>

<div class=3D"paragraph" style=3D"text-align:justify;">We also need to reme=
mber to take each of our values in the adjugate matrix modulo 26. So for ou=
r example we get the working below.<br></div>

<div><div class=3D"wsite-image wsite-image-border-none " style=3D"padding-t=
op:10px;padding-bottom:10px;margin-left:0;margin-right:0;text-align:center"=
>
<a href=3D"https://crypto.interactive-maths.com/uploads/1/1/3/4/11345755/99=
28545_orig.jpg" class=3D"w-fancybox">
<img src=3D"https://crypto.interactive-maths.com/uploads/1/1/3/4/11345755/9=
928545.jpg?658" alt=3D"Picture" style=3D"width:auto;max-width:100%">
</a>
<div style=3D"display:block;font-size:90%">Calculating the adjugate matrix =
of the key matrix.</div>
</div></div>

<div class=3D"paragraph" style=3D"text-align:justify;"><u>Step 3 - Multiply=
 the Multiplicative Inverse of the Determinant by the Adjugate Matrix</u><b=
r><span>To get the inverse key matrix, we now multiply the inverse determin=
ant (that was 19 in our case) from step 1 by each of the elements of the ad=
jugate matrix from step 2. Then we take each of these answers modulo 26.</s=
pan><br></div>

